Government wants to curb torture of 'witches', releases brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common traits.
They belong to the older generation, they cannot participate in work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
The one who "becomes" the witch is sent to isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"Men rarely make this fate."
"Young healthy women are not being removed because they help with work and give birth to children," says the order's sister, who cares for more than 100 women who have been expelled from their ranks in the West African capital of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to crack down on the unusual "social measure."
She has published an informational brochure to help curb the witch hunt.
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," die standard pointed out the disadvantage of written education.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after being tortured, dosed with kerosene and set on fire by three women and two men.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman ignited oil, which is used for ritual anointing.
It was said to have caught fire after the group wanted to "banish the evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education attained.
