Bakal's tenant: Drowns in stove, higher rent signed
An elderly stocky man stepped out the door of the client centre of RPG Byty "uhlobarona" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried a file and in it new leases for three apartments: his, his daughter and his son, who is in prison.
All three have just been deregulated.
Instead of 3500 per month, from next year the son will pay CZK 4100 for a 2+1 second category apartment.
"And there's no hot water, and it has to be heating with petrama (solid fuel stove, nb.)," the man points the finger at his son's new contract, for which he has the power of attorney.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry and half resigned.
The BytyOKD.cz, which called the new lease terms "incorrect and immoral," advises tenants not to sign new contracts and wait until December 7, when they will publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But a man just waves his hand at it.
"One says it, the other says it," he frowns.
Ostrava is becoming a great laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of apartments that still have non-market rents in the Czech Republic await.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The Havířov waiting room RPG is one of four in ostrava and on Tuesday at 9 am it is already full.
Right next to the door is security from the security agency and a caller.
"Rent 2011", a special button on its touchscreen is on.
One knock and a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
You won't even be able to read "157", and your number is already beeping on a large display under the ceiling of the waiting room.
In half a second, it's your turn.
After a while, an elderly married couple comes to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room clearly does not apply to the new rents at all.
Most people came to solve common problems as usual - claims for repairs, insurance claims and the like.
Letters with new leases are received in ostrava's mailboxes by tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio since about mid-November.
In letters, RPG Apartments proposes to increase their rent by 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the client centre on 18 November.
"It runs through the week, so it's only in the run-up," the workers behind the counter respond after a moment's hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakal's former mining apartments are a local hot topic.
Before the elections, the Deputy Speaker of parliament and Ostrava native Lubomír Zaorálek from the ČSSD took him in quite a bit, and even now the local newspaper is full of him.
"I want a new floor for 20 years."
"Not even a pos. and they didn't change my toilet board," the man says.
According to the workers, pensioners are coming most so far to see if they will get a rent discount if they sign on time, as RPG promises in the special offer.
Half the discount on february rent will also go to other tenants who sign the new contract by December 15.
However, the Havířov "deregulation" bulkhead is definitely not overwhelmed with questions.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 people were here for the 2011 rent," the workers behind the counter estimate.
The RPG proposes individual contracting where necessary on the website and its wall.
However, if both parties do not agree on the lease, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
"This is not a threat, but information about a possible and entirely legitimate legal procedure," the RPG warns on its website.
"No one's going to sue here," says one of the RPG Apartments workers, and the man on the street outside the client center partially rights her.
"I have a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left to eat, I don't have what it takes to sue," he says.
But the worker is immediately unsuased.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek is telling them in the media not to sign, so I guess people are waiting," he reflects.
Rent regulation ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty, their increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rent is still below the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing stock," says Pavel Klimeš, Director of the Residential Portfolio at RPG Byty, noting that the neglect of the housing stock is the main reason for the increase in rents, according to homeowners.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPG could invest four billion in apartments, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is supposed to be 5.2 billion.
Meanwhile, the large screen hanging from the ceiling opposite the padded seats of the miners' waiting room repeats a few red highlights.
"Rent increases of 15% or less in 2011 affect 31,200 apartments, that's more than 90% of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be the most by CZK 7.50 per square meter per month," it appears on the screen.
For only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio, the rent will increase by 38 percent.
"In these cases, this is an increase from an extremely low amount of CZK 19.66 per square metre," points out the RPG.
For 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive out rents in leaps and down, but will be spread over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds another commitment: all the money from the rent increase (see chart) will be put back into the apartments, mainly in heat savings - new windows and insulation.
They should preferably be given to people who sign an agreement to increase rents.
The offices also include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to also house a mini-school with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a pile of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees have been able to visit it.
The project-architectural company Arch.Design, from which a number of important Brno buildings emerged, had been counting on space for its company mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs almost 90 people, mostly babybooms, and cared that the women designers and architects could quickly return to work.
Together with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of the social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding employment with childcare.
The mini-school was invented by arch.design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to get a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant financing (subsidy in the amount of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operations for two years.
After exhausting the financial subsidy (2 years), the company Arch.Design to operate a mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The project took one year to prepare and Economy Rating significantly helped with the grant application.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are cared for all day by a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are over 3 years of age.
Since it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day more will be replaced.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework programme of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but also provide them with quality teaching - from basic cognition to preparation for school benches, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from kindergartens away from the parents' workplace are removed.
Parents thus use working hours more productively.
No wonder an employee-employer relationship is created here.
Arch.Design, he has become one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones still fascinates after 100 years. Check out Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizster, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are an open fish mouth.
Such is casa batlló house in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a façade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of Antoni Gaudí's Secession.
The façade of the house is played out by dream lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In detailed observation, you can see geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the whole façade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is lighted so that the impression of the shine of the colors is enhanced.
The venting and twisting of shapes also appears in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peephole and railings.
House Batlló, located in the Eixample district on the busy passeig de Grácia shopping street 43, was created by the reconstruction of the 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one, but soon accepted Gaudi's idea for an unusual and cheaper redevelopment.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment building himself.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the façade.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the façade.
Joint work on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house and Güell Park, which houses other works of Gaudí.
Soon after completion, the house earned the nickname "House of Bones" due to its organic shapes.
Others began to call it a "manly house" because of the specific window-opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs include other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree slope.
When creating Gaudí, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data he provided about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, during the completion, the city council was horrified by the result and asked for redress.
Councillors were annoyed, for example, that the building extended to the pillars and to the public sidewalk.
The correction never happened, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city council's call, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented out to a jewelry store.
The whole six-storey house is interseed by a staircase, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon door, and a larger society can communicate comfortably with each other without at the same time maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new façade, the house with Gaudí's reconstruction also received unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which are lined with an inner courtyard, and skylights is also impressive.
The two-color game adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark light, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló house, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most transparent and opulsable apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to do this only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They persisted in the tours as they found it to be a very profitable place and extended the tours to include common and attic areas, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is certainly not negligible, at €16.50, and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20% discount.
The sum far exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the true atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you need to quickly make friends with one of the inhabitants of the apartment building and visit it directly at home.
