More and more parents want to watch people, so they want to keep an eye on their children.
Fear for your own child is driving more and more people to the idea of gps monitoring.
The system originally designed for car searches can also track the movement of people and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anna Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were horrified by the case of missing Annie and began to look for means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of intruding on their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices can be misused, for example when they are put in a bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most of the time, customers actually buy it for safety reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what the purpose of the "box" is used and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything like this, they will simply get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to lose some things on purpose when they don't want to be in control."
"Mobile phones used to be very expected by parents, but they can be turned off just like these tracking devices," says Bočková.
According to it, it is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the upcoming abduction is to be made, the perpetrator will almost always ensure that the child does not have any electronics on him that could reveal his location."
"It's a phone now."
"When the tracking devices start to expand, they'll be looking for them, too, because their sales will surely be boosted by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of a call-up by a paedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers surveillance services for both cars and people, even if a tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to send location regularly after a certain period of time."
'Should it be damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned shall be available.'
"The more expensive devices have also built-in tiltometers, so even if one just slips and remains motionless, the device immediately sends a warning with a position," says The Czech.
According to him, smartphones with navigation can also take a similar service, where you can upload special software.
The problem with current tracking units is that they are either devices similar to pendants the size of matchboxes or smaller mobile phones.
They are always in danger of being lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, therefore, devices that look like a regular digital watch are now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that any aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he'll only know them after a while, and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the tracking devices develop into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology that is used to guard cars.
It is a combination of gps location (which is used by common autonavigation) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position of the car.
