Longer index finger than ring finger signs lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than their ring finger are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially when combined with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burdens, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men in parallel.
More than half of the study participants had an index finger shorter than the ring finger on their right hand.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those who had an index finger longer than their ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and for men under 60, the decrease was even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone promotes growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former Chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he was briefly known about this study, but he did not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
