These are some of the results of the current Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist.
As the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
This year's survey, which took place in September and early October, is dominated by two related issues.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several pacific rim countries in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced Democrats, which drags down the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but this is a big increase compared to 25% in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% said they trust the Parliament in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support was probably incurred during the global financial crisis because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission on Latin America reported this week that the ratio of Latinos living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009, falling again this year to 32.)
However, the mood changes in a wide range from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has become more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem (see Chart 5).
Some 31% say that either they or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but this is down from 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in growing support for private entrepreneurship and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say that private entrepreneurship is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that a market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same opinion (and 80% support private business there), although their leftist President Hugo Chávez expropriate many private firms.
Brazil is a leading country in the region, as 19% of respondents mentioned (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, up from 11% last year)
