Arsenic-resistant microbes increase the possibility of new life types on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the space for searching for new life forms on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it's a sign that life has possibilities that stand outside the main elements that have been considered and fundamental until now.
"This organism has a dual ability."
"It can grow either because of phosphorus or arsenic."
"This fact is very strange, but it is not evidence that it is some form of truly 'extraterrestrial' life," commented Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, six main elements were considered necessary for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sieera.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced with arsenic.
"You start to wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
This finding is important for finding life beyond Earth, because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life can look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on the news, released to discuss it, which did not reveal details of the find, sparked widespread speculation online that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to harness other elements that drive biochemistry, and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she considered that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace one after another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms can very difficult to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it does not work. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt to and grow.
Microbes grow better under phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility increases that a life form that uses arsenic may appear naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic that could be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example to prove it.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated that it may have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health
