In fact, it is a powerful marching simulation software that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes very far removed from automotive sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines in production plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision devices.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary mistakes and expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this software device has enabled the Red Bull team to make modifications and improvements "in a matter of hours, in near real time" that are otherwise detected during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in one period.
Red Bull now has 180 young, highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology who analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The Siemens manager explained that plm software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles, with the exception of the engine for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be translated from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using lasers and high-tech autoclave.
The only limit to this technical convenience is the $40 million amount representing the maximum any Formula One team can make for each period to improve their competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech plant about 30 miles from London to design and manufacture its racing cars.
These are two buildings that are restricted to visitors - especially journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered a "great secret".
The list of participants in this project includes 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's hero in Formula One is undoubtedly fresh champion Sebastian Vettel.
