How to interpret these emotiones?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here, Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which alludes to the idea of adhering to old traditions that a large part of the other members adhere to.
In the face of European resistance, there is speculation in Germany about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, for example, while southern countries would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to marce - although it may now seem like sci-fi, this version has broad public support, close to 50% of the population.
The third option, according to The German proposals, is to recast the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budgetary rigour, fines for guilty states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and an extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is now no room for dials.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission insuce deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany considered correct (plans for fiscal austerity and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country, as Merkel painfully dragged out decisions on greece's bailout.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to Greece's bailout.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has reappeared with a clear position, calling for the Reform of European Union Conventions to allow the rescue of a Member State, while at the same time allowing private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat softened form, has been approved, and in the coming months we should monitor the Union's reform process, which should allow for these measures from 2013 on.
Germany has set a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures need to be taken now, with which they seem to disagree too much, from this date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will represent the birth of a new currency zone, in which rule-breaking states will be severely sanctioned and forced to announce deferrals, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is suggesting to us that we must take a strict path of growth with an increase in savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital buffers.
They simply do not tolerate another debt-based and building-based option, with huge balance of payments gaps such as those that prevailed during Spain's boom years.
The offer is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand.
This is not just about restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
