Sport and circumvention of the rules
The tricks that Alonso and Ramos pulled off against Ajax show wit, not intent to escape punishment.
The allegedly concussed suspensions of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November have caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike conduct and whether or not UEFA should punish both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team clearly won), the named players deliberately wasted time one by one when a foul was about to be played to provoke the referee, who showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in the lead in their group - and will be able, deprived of their cards, to proceed to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Board gave coach Jose Mourinho a two-match suspension and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the eth of football, rules that are unwritten but watched.
Part of the discussion in this case arose from the fact that it involved a Real Madrid team (which prides itself on generosity and honour in its anthem, and which has already fined its players for similar acts), and, it seems, also thanks to the dramatisation led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
in any event, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts circumvent the law; these are indeed actions respecting sporting rules, the meaning of which, of course, seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is solved what type of damage such actions cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the elements of sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opponents, which in these cases was not violated, so there was no violent play.
Another of these elements that characterizes a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which has not happened here either.
So the paradox of the Real Madrid players' action is that there was no what we normally characterise as a ruse or circumvention of the law, there was no covert violation of the rules in order to avoid a penalty, but this behaviour should have been as noticeable as possible in order to receive the penalty.
They waited and were happy to receive the punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their intentional infraction.
It must be stated here that the opponent is not in a disadvantaged position and that there will be no benefit in the current match, since the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even that is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously is that players will start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardise their participation in the next match.
However, it is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by doing so, players will receive a penalty, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to exclude them.
So as the rounds go on, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players were not aimed at avoiding the award of a penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that this case was clearly about ingenuity.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because they were two self-separations, and because of the way in which the transmission of instructions to provoke them from the management took place.
The damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
