U.S. changes visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres before being interviewed by the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
From January 10, 2011, the visa process at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Centres of Services for Visa Applicants (short for ASC English) before an interview at the Consular Department.
Staff from the ASC will remove the applicant's biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a fee for the appointment, the second for processing the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current fare will remain unchanged: $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with an application (including visas for temporary workers), and $390 for a visa for merchants and investors.
People wishing to renew their visa will not have to be interviewed by a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and fingerprint them.
As biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
