World Plan for Lighting Restoration
In Cancún yesterday, the UN proposed a plan to restore home lighting, shop lighting and industrial space in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction in the greenhouse effect (GES), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional restrictions to be achieved to stabilize the planet's climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to promote in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace the hot bulbs, which still monopolise 50 to 70% of the market, with fluocompact bulbs or, better yet, bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LEDs" in English), a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) GES emissions generated on the planet due to lighting would be reduced.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from a car park on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe, and others, including Canada, participated in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance to stabilize climate warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to rule out that it will not get out of control.
In hot bulbs, 95% of energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new del bulbs, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, such as those launched this week by Philips - the company reportedly participated in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of a possible savings plan to be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be sorted as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless producers set up collection points.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants that emit much of the mercury needed to generate electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these headquarters put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation annually.
The report also details the profits that any country would make from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost $2.5 billion to build.
