Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test the promises made by developed countries to keep their promises of fast-start or early start financing.
And the great French hacks have been exposed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union promised €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (that is, €420 million a year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its fast start funding commitment: a report specifying its Member States' action, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to keep its promise of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we'll find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are 'new and additional' to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been preserved, and it is adding 150 million for three years of fast-start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or with public aid for development.
France, on the other hand, considered that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 was 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to previous period expenditure or to the global level of Public Aid for the Development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, france's total aid intensity vis-à-vis developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), it is to honour its commitment to finance "new and additional "...
Another decisive element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as The New York Times, have been in the market for a new France, they are considering that 1€ borrowed equals 1€ donated.
Clearly, this is hardly demonstrable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reductions, consisting in more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present the one euro we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not see it as the price of a loan to a creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France can only give such a justification: it "admopocalyphates" its €420 million commitment, of which it makes a 91.5% loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only Country of the Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany claimed 46% from here, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are keeping their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to back up its promise, France gives only 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
Beautiful juggler's piece!
To sum up, in its fast-start financing, France operates with double swindling: on the one hand, the development of the stock over time and, on the other hand, the real financial burden.
Although it spends only €36.1 million, it can convince that it issuing €420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Finance Minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when all they have to do is lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not entirely naïve...
The early funding chapter is a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever this is, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing deposits (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how loans are accounted for.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting hope in the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward with the discussions.
